Alright, so you want to automate the selection of all checkboxes on a page and then save them with a click on a "Save" button. Here's how you can do it:

1. **Select All Checkboxes**: You can use `document.querySelectorAll` to select all the checkboxes.
2. **Check Each Checkbox**: Loop through the selected checkboxes and set their `checked` property to `true`.
3. **Handle Button Click**: Add an event listener to your "Save" button to trigger the checkbox selection.

Here’s a quick example using plain JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Checkbox Automation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="saveButton">Save</button>

    <div>
        <input type="checkbox" name="option1"> Option 1<br>
        <input type="checkbox" name="option2"> Option 2<br>
        <input type="checkbox" name="option3"> Option 3<br>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Select all checkboxes
        const checkboxes = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]');

        // Function to check all checkboxes
        function checkAll() {
            checkboxes.forEach(checkbox => {
                checkbox.checked = true;
            });
        }

        // Get the save button and add an event listener
        const saveButton = document.getElementById('saveButton');
        saveButton.addEventListener('click', checkAll);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example:
- We first select all the checkboxes using `document.querySelectorAll`.
- Then we define a function `checkAll` that loops through each checkbox and sets its `checked` property to `true`.
- Finally, we attach an event listener to the "Save" button that calls the `checkAll` function when clicked.

This way, when you click the "Save" button, all checkboxes will be checked!

